{
  "title": "The Curious Child",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "edb971719614eda2",
      "text": "During our preparation to open Griffin State School in 2015, Vicki connected us to the _Curiosity and Powerful Learning_ (CPL) Brisbane network. Authored by Wayne Craig and Professor David Hopkins and published by McRel International, CPL is a school improvement framework with curiosity at its core. Our continued work with Wayne Craig and the network has broadened our understanding about the nature of curiosity and how we might best harness it as a powerful tool for learning. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5814a13df897cfb8",
      "text": "Many say that Alice, from _Alice in Wonderland_, is the supreme model of the curious child. A child innately following her own interests, instinctively questioning, pondering and wandering; a self-motivated learner driven by her why’s and how’s to explore Wonderland. Within the seven _Curiosity and Powerful Learning_ manuals, Alice and her journey through Wonderland is used as an example of teaching for curiosity and the associated transformation pedagogy can take. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b742e725f6850db8",
      "text": "Craig and his work has lead us to explore the two types of curiosity, exploratory and intellectual, or epistemic, curiosity. The first helping us to examine how we spark interest, inspire genuine questioning and provoke risk taking. The second challenging us to ponder how we might ignite curious thinking through the opportunities we curate and the guidance we provide. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fdaf82f7b1bdba11",
      "text": "Developing our understanding about the nature of curiosity has allowed us to think more critically about our planning and how [[Opportunities over Activities]] and [[Powerful Provocations]] might better cater for how children innately learn. If we hold the image of Alice in our mind when designing classroom experiences, the nature of our role shifts too. In better understanding curiosity, we are designing fewer experiences where we are the ‘sage on the stage’ and are more deeply considering how we might be the ‘guide on the side’, noticing and spurring Alice along in her journey. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "03024e26ff7cfa31",
      "text": "If we want our children to be authentic learning seekers, then understanding how we best encourage this behaviour is crucial. Understanding the role that curiosity can play and how best to harness this gift of childhood at school continues to be an important focus for educators at Griffin. After all, if we want our learners to leave us [[Literate, Numerate and Curious]], we must not only preserve curiosity but also magnify its power and make this explicit to learners. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7b2e4aed0f2a5f53",
      "text": "Next: [[Opportunities over Activities]]"
